<subSubSection id="DC3B90D009236CBDF64B788863DBB11A" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" type="tl">
<paragraph id="F9E6742C9DED7A1BCF19070170E27B6F" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">TL.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A9C0DDC9E3EEE3CE78EEA26AB1009889" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">
The type locality was originally stated as 
<normalizedToken id="9C06817F54E318E77B95241378103119" originalValue="‘Australia’">'Australia'</normalizedToken>
(
<bibRefCitation id="E5513FB41E7FB4B9F24E81E9F039C3A6" author="Sowerby, GB II" journalOrPublisher="Sowerby, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" publicationUrl="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/8209501" refId="B121" refString="Sowerby, GB II, 1872. Monograph of the genus Limnaea. In: Reeve L. Conchologia Iconica. L. Reeve and Co, London, 18, no pagination, plates 1-15. https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/8209501" title="Monograph of the genus Limnaea. In: Reeve L. Conchologia Iconica. L. Reeve and Co, London, 18, no pagination, plates 1 - 15." url="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/8209501" year="1872">Sowerby 1872</bibRefCitation>
). It is, however, erroneous. 
<bibRefCitation id="E2E2AAEBC894E8C78CFD24FC10B41236" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.96210" author="Hanley, S" journalOrPublisher="Reeve and Co, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" refId="B48" refString="Hanley, S, Theobald, W, 1876. Conchologia Indica: Illustrations of the Land and Freshwater Shells of British India. L. Reeve and Co, London, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.96210" title="Conchologia Indica: Illustrations of the Land and Freshwater Shells of British India. L." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.96210" year="1876">Hanley and Theobald (1876)</bibRefCitation>
gave the proper type locality: Kashmir.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="72FB4605F3A2F880947AACE0996F0EDD" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" type="types">
<paragraph id="1D425B0614695503BBA74CED17B2DE9F" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">Types.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2EC31340D46BB7C461A03C61452CE033" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">NHMUK. The syntypes were inspected by us.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="69E0395FC7226CAFE043A95C70FE6CDC" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">
<taxonomicName id="7EA4F3DBF10D91A8E66B0DC3E5999C03" genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis id="0E6882E7F25528AE40EEA9F87E18413E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabits Northern India (Kashmir), Nepal, China (Western Tibet and Himalaya Range) and, probably, Tajikistan (Pamir Mts.) [
<bibRefCitation id="092A795B83C6BAF2F26CB367664B18E4" author="Subba Rao, MV" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Survey of India, Calcutta" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" refId="B126" refString="Subba Rao, MV, 1989. Handbook: Freshwater Molluscs of India. Zoological Survey of India, Calcutta" title="Handbook: Freshwater Molluscs of India." year="1989">Subba Rao 1989</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="F981DEA7E631933FF6EFADFCDCAD52FF" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" author="Gloeer, P" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" pagination="137 - 156" refId="B43" refString="Gloeer, P, Boessneck, U, 2013. Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species. Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde 142: 137 - 156, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" title="Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" volume="142" year="2013">
<normalizedToken id="0598C6F94AB1AC8F38D545E206E49A87" originalValue="Glöer">Gloeer</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken id="7F9174FFED9FA3673334104F1784CF31" originalValue="Bössneck">Boessneck</normalizedToken>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="F66F38B661E53BF08A8B6BE7BE351EAF" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-29451-1" author="Aksenova, OV" journalOrPublisher="Scientific Reports" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" pagination="1 - 17" refId="B1" refString="Aksenova, OV, Bolotov, IN, Gofarov, MY, Kondakov, AV, Vinarski, MV, Bespalaya, YV, Kolosova, YS, Palatov, DM, Sokolova, SE, Spitsyn, VM, Tomilova, AA, Travina, OV, Vikhrev, IV, 2018a. Species richness, molecular taxonomy and biogeography of the radicine pond snails (Gastropoda: Lymnaeidae) in the Old World. Scientific Reports 8 (11199): 1 - 17, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-29451-1" title="Species richness, molecular taxonomy and biogeography of the radicine pond snails (Gastropoda: Lymnaeidae) in the Old World." url="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-29451-1" volume="8" year="2018 a">Aksenova et al. 2018a</bibRefCitation>
]. The record of this species from Tajikistan is based on numerous shells from ZISP collection (see Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5CC916E0CD196B27F3370CA457DD2C32" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Shells of species in the genus Radix. A. Radix auricularia (28.08.2013, Kazakhstan, Karaganda Region, Suresai River; LMBI); B. R. alticola (20.06.2012, Tajikistan, a hot spring near Djelandy village; LMBI); C. R. alticola (01.07.2016, Tajikistan, a warm brook near Dzhaushangoz village; LMBI); D. R. brevicauda (Kashmir, a syntype; NHMUK); E. R. brevicauda (05.08.1948, Tajikistan, Pamir Mts., Shaimak village, in a warm spring; ZISP); F. R. euphratica (26.06.2016, Tajikistan, Dushanbe, a fountain near the President's palace; LMBI); G. R. euphratica (04.07.2016, Tajikistan, a roadside ditch near Kurban-Shakhid village; LMBI); H. R. euphratica (without date, Iraq, Bagdad; NHMUK); I. R. makhrovi, the holotype (China, Tibet, a roadside ditch west of the Lhasa River mouth; ZISP); J. R. plicatula, a probable syntype (China, Chusan, NHMUK); K. R. plicatula (26.07.2017, China, Uyghuria, Bagrash-kol' Lake; LMBI); L. R. plicatula (26.11.2014, China, Bejing, an artificial pond in the former Emperor's summer palace; LMBI). Scale bars: 2 mm (B-C, F-L), 5 mm (A, D-E, K)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.52860.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448267" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">3E</figureCitation>
), virtually identical with the syntypes of 
<taxonomicName id="8D21B72D58F55755645475444ADAF539" genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis id="090EDC2142B1168FD07BA7507D5D0FC8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This species has not been registered from the ex-USSR territory (
<bibRefCitation id="FF769ACA106434E6190D1514EF343753" author="Vinarski, MV" journalOrPublisher="Severtsov Institute of Ecology and Evolution of RAS, Moscow" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" refId="B142" refString="Vinarski, MV, Kantor, YI, 2016. Analytical catalogue of fresh and brackish water molluscs of Russia and adjacent countries. A.N. Severtsov Institute of Ecology and Evolution of RAS, Moscow" title="Analytical catalogue of fresh and brackish water molluscs of Russia and adjacent countries. A. N." year="2016">Vinarski and Kantor 2016</bibRefCitation>
) and hereby we, for the first time, include it in the malacofauna of the former Soviet Union. However, this record is still not corroborated genetically.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C57610719D1835EA264ABF574AF7F6C4" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">
The shell of 
<taxonomicName id="722E74FF7D8DCFC51597D82022B8AD74" genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis id="7FD90BBCA9490E75638558DB5E35D575" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is ear-shaped, with low spire and greatly expanded aperture. Generally, in many ways, it resembles the shell of 
<taxonomicName id="775A146279D5275976C512583D98AA8A" genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis id="FBB588F13091001D09566F351A4185A3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="06FE1BF0DCD00433134FA0A0AAB7C2EF" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" author="Gloeer, P" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" pagination="137 - 156" refId="B43" refString="Gloeer, P, Boessneck, U, 2013. Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species. Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde 142: 137 - 156, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" title="Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" volume="142" year="2013">
<normalizedToken id="4FC0BBD355117B0429E3A135F87DB219" originalValue="Glöer">Gloeer</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken id="5A6883F1B15C267ACB72F4D41C2DFE6F" originalValue="Bössneck">Boessneck</normalizedToken>
(2013
</bibRefCitation>
: 153) note that there are no substantial differences between the two species, which are probable synonyms. However, 
<bibRefCitation id="B81F881DC161B2A30DD1749C7FF823EC" author="Annandale, N" journalOrPublisher="Records of the Indian Museum" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" pagination="137 - 189" publicationUrl="http://faunaofindia.nic.in/PDFVolumes/records/027/03/0137-0189.pdf" refId="B13" refString="Annandale, N, Rao, HS, 1925. Materials for a revision of the recent Indian Limnaeidae (Mollusca Pulmonata). Records of the Indian Museum 27: 137 - 189, http://faunaofindia.nic.in/PDFVolumes/records/027/03/0137-0189.pdf" title="Materials for a revision of the recent Indian Limnaeidae (Mollusca Pulmonata)." url="http://faunaofindia.nic.in/PDFVolumes/records/027/03/0137-0189.pdf" volume="27" year="1925">Annandale and Rao (1925)</bibRefCitation>
reported the structure of the jaw and radula of 
<taxonomicName id="A96F1E4A98A3EFF96E9C3FF0B4DC5FFA" genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis id="1B20FA8662AA9476F8576E8D9BBF3B01" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinct from that of 
<taxonomicName id="2CCF12475FB3E1EEAC8443D924700A18" genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis id="397679A8E6C934D051F8EE2C5FB36487" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The anatomical structure of the discussed species, described and illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation id="E9656DBCDBA26B713537D509150227E1" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" author="Gloeer, P" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" pagination="137 - 156" refId="B43" refString="Gloeer, P, Boessneck, U, 2013. Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species. Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde 142: 137 - 156, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" title="Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" volume="142" year="2013">
<normalizedToken id="5D7E792B4E8F307F8DB72F1440164845" originalValue="Glöer">Gloeer</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken id="E34977DD403AED6B501A10DDBF421B31" originalValue="Bössneck">Boessneck</normalizedToken>
(2013)
</bibRefCitation>
, is typical for the genus 
<taxonomicName id="2C0C940B4E4626356FD8347A74C1A32D" class="Gastropoda" family="Lymnaeidae" genus="Radix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Radix" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D001D18457C6F1922D6E101C14E7A471" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">Radix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Our molecular analysis recovered 
<taxonomicName id="902B495D4E820446FA2ED3EFFA6B1964" genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis id="73B28FD3C6E1F0EEED251EB47DAAEAA6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a species sister to 
<taxonomicName id="8230276294EA62C40A1174F378ABC700" genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis id="9C000E08E7BF3A24F1723D94411D9063" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="CB980C1254963B5EBB48CB1B10F10661" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-29451-1" author="Aksenova, OV" journalOrPublisher="Scientific Reports" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" pagination="1 - 17" refId="B1" refString="Aksenova, OV, Bolotov, IN, Gofarov, MY, Kondakov, AV, Vinarski, MV, Bespalaya, YV, Kolosova, YS, Palatov, DM, Sokolova, SE, Spitsyn, VM, Tomilova, AA, Travina, OV, Vikhrev, IV, 2018a. Species richness, molecular taxonomy and biogeography of the radicine pond snails (Gastropoda: Lymnaeidae) in the Old World. Scientific Reports 8 (11199): 1 - 17, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-29451-1" title="Species richness, molecular taxonomy and biogeography of the radicine pond snails (Gastropoda: Lymnaeidae) in the Old World." url="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-29451-1" volume="8" year="2018 a">Aksenova et al. 2018a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D3AC13317D2CF78912064CADABD0FA0E" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">
We may indicate some conchological differences between 
<taxonomicName id="9B8B8A7840ED6F4792AFA61AEF7C1BBC" genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis id="2BAFB15D8B93DBBF938535C5F6E55F29" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="EAB7FC384268EA5361AF3FB30948EAC0" genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis id="B0EA4B634A2A74BED8933820B2975981" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The latter species is of smaller size, the largest syntype shell is 18.1 mm (our data) and 
<bibRefCitation id="1CA2509A0C7EE17BEDC4357478D70CEA" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" author="Gloeer, P" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" pagination="137 - 156" refId="B43" refString="Gloeer, P, Boessneck, U, 2013. Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species. Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde 142: 137 - 156, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" title="Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" volume="142" year="2013">
<normalizedToken id="A8CD6B8D1B6C8D018AC3048B382DDB6B" originalValue="Glöer">Gloeer</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken id="82E17F96BC962F26BFAAD1A78AE6551B" originalValue="Bössneck">Boessneck</normalizedToken>
(2013)
</bibRefCitation>
mention that 
<taxonomicName id="D575A76AA659C022BEB3D495714D84AC" genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis id="E9B0C5B3E170159656CC91615BECD65B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may reach 20 mm in height. Next, the columellar depression in shells of 
<taxonomicName id="005D6790B41827E70B2F582469B5383E" genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis id="9F8839815F97E8E977BB49962B1B8E7E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very prominent, whereas, in 
<taxonomicName id="441B91958971A17C825DC94B48E95B62" genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis id="53F4F87C782C99A5A547CD2F03A42C63" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it is typically weakly developed (compare Fig. 
<figureCitation id="61D35F1ACB91F88BD3F5E06949DF4515" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. The scheme of measurements of the shell (A) and the parts of the copulatory apparatus (B). Abbreviations: SH - shell height; SW - shell width; SpH - spire height; BWH - body whorl height; AH - aperture height; AW - aperture width; PP - length of praeputium; PS - penis sheath length. A - after Vinarski (2016 b)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.52860.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448266" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">2A</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation id="65B62F966C78784194E8388E37F66573" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. The scheme of measurements of the shell (A) and the parts of the copulatory apparatus (B). Abbreviations: SH - shell height; SW - shell width; SpH - spire height; BWH - body whorl height; AH - aperture height; AW - aperture width; PP - length of praeputium; PS - penis sheath length. A - after Vinarski (2016 b)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.52860.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448266" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">2D, E</figureCitation>
). Lastly, the spire whorls in 
<taxonomicName id="8DD1D8BEA918EDD83B81EF0FAE55DFD8" genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis id="B49D9227CCC0D75946938131065C7E18" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are usually flattened, while in 
<taxonomicName id="1480349558843452C5B956951DC60B7D" genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis id="8F16DB79E6236A82E0E19D3BAC90F67B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
these are visibly convex and rounded.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="036289C8C19CAAE756E8CB5A156FDB6F" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" type="nomenclature remark">
<paragraph id="D746E5C2B63460B6200F6E6A0667C9B8" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">Nomenclature remark.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="10BEE0178004CD38FD2F219D86D574F2" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">
The name 
<taxonomicName id="381A23880ED9BC7F2E243F86F0EF2008" authority="Blainville, 1824" authorityName="G.B.Sowerby II" authorityYear="1872" class="Gastropoda" family="Lymnaeidae" genus="Limnaea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Limnaea brevicauda" order="Hygrophila" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis id="EBDA06AF56C9153308CB1C159504B68B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">Limnaea brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Sowerby is the oldest available one to designate a lymnaeid species, sister to 
<taxonomicName id="45A58EC04FE8302780025B6197F47F7A" genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis id="A9962D6BB16627A2702C8F1A0E98821C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, restricted in its distribution to the Central Asia mountain regions. The taxonomic identity of 
<taxonomicName id="FA3C51E3520D210FBC04E2AE0041C71F" genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis id="1EB5B93C66577A32CA0127E9FB547437" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as well its close affinity to 
<taxonomicName id="C6EF49AA778D4F1E22E3F4CB9169ED84" genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis id="CB4BDC48CFF82D3D8A3A2241A0C502AF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, was confirmed by the inspection of the extant syntypes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
